We may now turn to the actual use of the tally, especially as this point is nowhere dealt with in the Drblogvr. An accountant coming to make his Easter proffer would pay into the Exchequer a certain amount of money; this amount would be recorded upon a tally in the way described above, and the tally would then be split down the middle for about threeouarters of its length, and part cut off ; the foil, or smaller part, was then given to the accountant, and the stock, or larger part ², retained in the Enchequer. Beyond this, another usage arose at an early date. The tally became regarded as a species of currency.
